Also, the fact that we even CAN create positive change is just endlessly interesting! So of course we want to play around with it and deepen our understanding of our power.

Here’s your CARD OF THE DAY: Land of Dreams from THE ORACLE OF PORTALS.

Before bed tonight, place a journal or a notebook and a pen near your bed. As you’re drifting off to sleep, bring a question or situation you’d like more clarity on into your mind. Focus on it and wonder about it without worrying about it too much. Just hold it lightly in your thoughts with curiosity and openness. Ask for divine support on receiving helpful guidance on this issue while you sleep. 

If you wake in the night and remember a dream, turn on your light and write it down. Otherwise, write down any dreams you remember upon waking in the morning. Also, write down any impressions or realizations that may have dawned on you upon wakening. 

Once you’re fully awake, read over what you’ve written. With each dream, ask yourself, “If had to guess what this dream was about, what would I guess? What aspect of my life might this dream relate to?” Take whatever time you need to process and contemplate everything you wrote.

I just love it when a sabbat coincides with a full moon – don’t you?

This year, we have the Aquarius full moon on Lughnasadh, August 1st. (This is, of course, not Lughnasadh but Imbolc if you’re in the Southern Hemisphere.)

Aquarius is the sign of the visionary: it fuels our uniqueness and magnifies our desire to help bring about positive change in our lives, our relationships, our communities, and our world.

The Aquarius full moon (and this sabbat) always fall in Leo season, which is the time when the sun is in its native sign of Leo: the sign of the self and the heart. Leo season is an excellent time to work on self-love, self-trust, and self-approval. Lughnasadh, named after the Celtic god Lugh (whose name means “Light”), is a natural match for Leo season as a celebration of the inspiring, bolstering, and health-giving properties of light and the sun.

During this extra magical time, we also happen to be in a Venus retrograde period. While this can be stormy with regards to love and romance (particularly with regards to your own needs, desires, and boundaries with this retrograde in Leo), it can also ultimately be a time of deep healing, purification, and restructuring in these areas as well. If something uncomfortable comes up for you in one of these areas, be willing to face it. Get in touch with what you truly need and desire in order to heal old relationship patterns while being true to yourself. Then speak your truth and enforce your boundaries. Whatever happens as a result, surrender to the process of change and uncertainty. By the time the retrograde period is over on September 3rd, you’ll have more clarity and will be ready to move forward in whatever way is most ideal for you.

Day 3: Plan to volunteer.

Volunteering is a magical act. In addition to supporting others, it also supports your own happiness and wellbeing.

And, magically speaking, what you send out comes back to you multiplied. So volunteering is also prosperity magic.

Do you already have a volunteer gig you love? Great! Enjoy it.

Otherwise, investigate and brainstorm ideas for how you can show up for a cause you care about once a week, bi-weekly, or whatever works best for you. Look for ways to serve that might be enjoyable to you, so you can sustain them over time.

(Ideas: distribute food at a local food pantry, volunteer at a local historical society, take a shelter dog for a walk.)

No need to start a new gig during the holiday season, unless you want to. (That could be perfect, but it also might be a lot.) Instead, you can make a plan for how you can start getting out there in the new year. Perhaps send an email to a volunteer coordinator or turn to January in your calendar and pencil in a date to take action on your idea.
